Generated by AIHow four components quietly turned one page visit into four API calls
A few days ago I was chasing down what looked like a completely unrelated bug — a schema validation error showing up after a delete operation that had actually succeeded. While adding some diagnostic logging to track it down, I noticed something odd in my server logs: a single page visit was hitting my API four times for the exact same data.
No errors. No crashes. Just four identical requests, silently, every time.
Here’s what caused it, how I proved it wasn’t what I first assumed, and the one-line fix.
The setup
Say you have a product list page built the way most Nuxt apps naturally end up structured: one “list” component that fetches and displays the data, plus a handful of modal components for creating, editing, and deleting items — all rendered together on the same page.
<!-- ProductList.vue -->
<script setup lang="ts">
const { products, refresh } = useProducts()
</script><template>
<div v-for="product in products" :key="product.id">
{{ product.name }}
</div>
<CreateProductModal v-model:open="isCreateOpen" @success="refresh" />
<EditProductModal v-model:open="isEditOpen" @success="refresh" />
<DeleteProductModal v-model:open="isDeleteOpen" @success="refresh" />
</template>
Each modal also calls useProducts(), because it needs the mutation functions and a helper to look up a specific product by ID:
// CreateProductModal.vue
const { addProduct } = useProducts()// EditProductModal.vue
const { getProductById, updateProduct } = useProducts()
// DeleteProductModal.vue
const { getProductById, deleteProduct } = useProducts()
And the composable itself, built the standard way with useAsyncData:
// useProducts.ts
export const useProducts = () => {
const { data: products, refresh, pending, error } = useAsyncData(
'products',
() => $fetch('/api/products'),
{ server: false }
) const addProduct = async (payload) => { /* ... */ }
const updateProduct = async (id, payload) => { /* ... */ }
const deleteProduct = async (id) => { /* ... */ }
const getProductById = (id) => products.value?.find(p => p.id === id)
return { products, refresh, pending, error, addProduct, updateProduct, deleteProduct, getProductById }
}
This looks completely reasonable. It’s the pattern most tutorials show, and it’s what I’d written across half a dozen similar composables in this codebase before noticing anything was wrong.
The problem
useAsyncData defaults immediate to true [1] "If false, prevents function from being called immediately." That means: as soon as the composable is called, it fetches — no explicit trigger needed, and nothing in the code has to ask for it.
The catch is that every single call to useProducts() counts, not just the "main" one in ProductList.vue. Since CreateProductModal, EditProductModal, and DeleteProductModal are all rendered on the page (not lazily, not behind a route change — just conditionally visible via v-model:open), all four components call useProducts() when the page mounts. And since immediate: true is the default, all four can trigger their own fetch for the same 'products' key.
They do share state — useAsyncData calls with the same key share the same data, pending, and error refs. But sharing the result isn't the same as deduplicating the request. Whether four near-simultaneous calls collapse into one network request or fire as four separate ones depends on whether they land in the same synchronous tick of Vue's component initialization — and that's not something you can rely on.
First guess: “it’s just dev mode”
My first instinct, honestly, was to blame the dev server. I’d heard the general folklore that things “run twice” in development — React’s StrictMode does this on purpose, and there are a handful of documented Nuxt/Vue issues about duplicate useAsyncData calls tied to <Suspense> nesting and dev-mode plugin loading. It felt like a safe, low-effort explanation.
So I tested it properly instead of assuming. I added a request counter with timestamps directly in the API route:
export default defineEventHandler(async (event) => {
console.log(`[GET /api/products] invocation at ${Date.now()}`)
// ...
})First visit to the page: exactly 1 request. Leave the page, come back: 4 requests, all within ~164ms of each other.
That inconsistency alone (1, then 4 — not a clean 2x every time) was already a hint that this wasn’t a simple “everything doubles” dev-mode quirk. So I built the app for production and ran the compiled server directly, no Vite dev server, no HMR, nothing dev-specific in the loop at all:
npm run build
node .output/server/index.mjsSame result. 1, then 4.
That settled it. This wasn’t dev tooling. It was a structural issue in the component tree, and it would affect every real user in production, every time they navigated away from and back to that page.
The fix
The fix is small once you know where to look: only one component should ever trigger the fetch. Everyone else should just consume the shared state.
// useProducts.ts
export const useProducts = () => {
const { data: products, refresh, pending, error } = useAsyncData(
'products',
() => $fetch('/api/products'),
{
server: false,
immediate: false, // <- nothing auto-fetches anymore
}
) // ...same as before
}
<!-- ProductList.vue -->
<script setup lang="ts">
const { products, refresh } = useProducts()// This is now the ONE place that triggers the initial load.
refresh()
</script>
The three modals still call useProducts() for their mutation functions and getProductById, but since none of them call refresh() themselves, they never trigger a fetch of their own. They simply read whatever ProductList.vue already loaded, via the shared products ref.
Verifying the fix
Same test, same page, same “leave and come back” flow. This time: exactly 1 request, every time, in production.
The takeaway
If you have a composable built on useAsyncData that's called from more than one component on the same page — a list view plus its own create/edit/delete modals is an extremely common shape for this — check whether more than one of those components is capable of triggering the fetch. immediate: true (the default) means any call to the composable can fire a request, not just the one you think of as "the" call site.
The fix costs one line (immediate: false) plus one explicit refresh() call in whichever component should actually own the initial load. But finding it requires knowing to look — the bug produces no errors, no console warnings, nothing that flags itself. It just quietly sends more requests than you think it does, and the only way to really know is to count them.
One habit worth adopting from this: write immediate: true (or false) explicitly, every time, even though true is already the default. The entire bug above existed because the default was invisible — nobody writing the first useAsyncData call had to consciously decide "should this auto-fetch, given that three other components also call this composable?" An implicit default doesn't ask that question; an explicit one does. Spelling it out costs nothing and turns an invisible assumption into something a reviewer — or you, six months later — can actually see and question, before a second and third component start calling the same composable.
If you’re debugging something that looks like a “dev mode does something weird” issue, it’s worth the five extra minutes to build for production and test again before you commit to that explanation. It’s very often not the dev server’s fault.
Happy Coding!
References:
[1] useAsyncData · Nuxt Composables v4
